Data Roles

  • In sample :
  • Out of sample :
  • Out of time :
  • In sample Training Test

Training Dataset

  • The training set shold :
    • be representative of the entire data set
    • cover the full range of values for all the predictors that the model might encounter
    • contain a sufficient number of observations of rare events (i.e.balancing the outputs)
  • A random sample of available data are not sufficient since the rare observations may not be chosen. Solution: startified sampling ( )
    • rare observation , , training test
    • , Training/Test , Trainin/Test

Test Dataset

set.seed(1234) # train/test     ,    
i = sample(1:nrow(buytest), round(nrow(buytest)*0.7)) #70% for training data, 30% for testdata
train = buytest[i,] 
test = buytest[-i,]

paste0('Train: ',nrow(train), ', Test: ', nrow(test))
## [1] "Train: 7000, Test: 3000"

train=na.omit(train)

model1 = glm(RESPOND~AGE+BUY12+BUY18+FICO+MARRIED+OWNHOME,family=binomial(),data=train)
model2 = glm(RESPOND~AGE+FICO+MARRIED+OWNHOME,family=binomial(),data=train)

2. Lift (Gain) charts

  • The scored data set is sorted by the posterior probabilities of the event level in descending order
  • The observations are then grouped into deciles
  • The x-axis is sample size or proportion
  • The y-axis can be
    1. % Captured Response :
    2. % Response : (1 )
    3. Lift : (/= xx) > xx



Generating a lift chart

| Decile | Frequency of buy | % Captured Response | % Response | Lift | |::|::|::|::|::| ##TBD |1 | 174|174/381=45.6 |174/200|87/19=4.57| |2 | 110|110/381=28.8 |174/200|87/19=4.57| |3 | 38 |38/381=9.9 |174/200|87/19=4.57| |4 | 14 |14/381=3.6 |174/200|87/19=4.57| |5 | 11 |11/381=2.8 |174/200|87/19=4.57| |6 | 10 |10/381=2.6 |174/200|87/19=4.57| |7 | 7 | 7/381=1.8 |174/200|87/19=4.57| |8 | 10 |10/381=2.6 |174/200|87/19=4.57| |9 | 3 |3/381=0.7 |174/200|87/19=4.57| |10| 4 |4/381=1.0 |174/200|87/19=4.57|

  • Baseline Lift = 381/2000 = 19.05%

AUROC

  • Area under the ROC curve : AUROC = (Ar+1)/2
    • ROC
  • AUROC max 100%, min 50%
    • 0.8 : good
    • 0.75 : moderate
    • 0.65 :
  • AR AUROC 1:1 
### ROC  ###
#install.packages("pROC",repos="http://healthstat.snu.ac.kr/CRAN/")
library(pROC)
## Type 'citation("pROC")' for a citation.
## 
## Attaching package: 'pROC'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     cov, smooth, var
roccurve1 <- roc(test$RESPOND ~ prob_pred1)
plot(roccurve1)

auc(roccurve1) # AUROC
## Area under the curve: 0.6351
roccurve2 <- roc(test$RESPOND ~ prob_pred2)
plot(roccurve2)

auc(roccurve2) # AUROC
## Area under the curve: 0.6086
